with a group of six wizards in a few seconds.<br>
<br>
So, the solution then is to stop this static zone setup.<br>
<br>
The solution in my opinion is to stop saying that those who buy expansions get new abilities for their characters, in addition to the new content.<br>
<br>
Those who never bought an expansion should have been allowed to go up to level 60.  They still couldn't go to Kunark or the other lands, so this would limit their access to spells and to group to get equipment.  They would end up with the scraps since they could never get NO DROP items that drop in expansions.  This would also allow Verant to boost the level on dragons such as Vox and Naggy, and then forcing those encounters to be &quot;off limits&quot; to high level characters would be gone.<br>
<br>
Alternate Advancement should have been opened up to everyone.  There's no trainers, or guild masters that teach AA abilities, they just &quot;come to us&quot; when we spend the points.  So why not give this to everyone of the appropriate level?<br>
<br>
Mobs over 32k HP should be the rule across the game once Velious came out.  This does NOT mean that all mobs would be made more powerful, just that the HP on those dragons and perhaps some other mobs would be higher, their damage output lowered, and that would maintain the current difficulty.<br>
<br>
Loot rewards MUST be changed as well I feel to reflect the current nature of the game.  Should Vox and Naggy drop items a level 60 would want if the game design says that level 60s shouldn't be killing those mobs?  Should tough boss-mob encounters drop items that are considered pathetic in comparison to the current availability of items?  A number of epic items are out-classed by drops from Velious and Luclin, so it should be time for either an upgrade, or an second phase to epic quests that would allow upgrades to epic items.<br>
<br>
Kunark out-classed Antonica/Faydwer/Odus, Velious out-classed Kunark, and finally we have Luclin, which doesn't turn Velious items into worthless items when fighting mobs, so Verant DID learn, but why can't they apply what they learned to the older zones?<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 60 Wizard<br>
The First Seal<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
