<br>
Obviously, SOME balance will need to be done with the loot drops as well from mobs, and perhaps some zone upgrades as well, but this would make the older zones see more usage.<br>
<br>
Another way to look at this:<br>
<br>
If old world zone designed for levels 15 to 30 were to drop items that would be desired by people with all expansions, old and new, people of those levels would probably want to go there.<br>
<br>
If old world zone designed for level 35 to 50 were to drop items that would be desired in this level range for people with all expansions, people would go there.<br>
<br>
If old world zone has loot that used to be good, but now has poor loot and XP reward compared to similar level zones from the newer expansions, those with the newer expansions will NOT go there.<br>
<br>
What we have seen from EQ has supported this.  Mistmoore, once a heavily used hunting spot for those level 20 to 50 is now largely empty due to newer zones being better in many ways.  Unrest also doesn't have the population levels it once had, not because there are more zones, but because many realize that there is BETTER loot and XP to be had in other zones with a similar level of difficulty.<br>
<br>
These are only two examples, but the same thing applies to many of the &quot;unused zones&quot; in the game.  If the loot and/or XP arn't enough to justify going there, people won't go.  Sure, the zones may be FANTASTIC for design and content, but if they are out of the way, there needs to be more incentive.  What about increasing coin drop for example, so that the deeper you go, the more money you get.  If items arn't going to be added, having mobs drop 30 plat each might inspire those who need money to buy other things to go there.  How about tradeskills?  We have a few places to farm spider silk, I can bet that if the kaesora spiders dropped on average 4 spider silks that the place would see more action.<br>
<br>
So, boost the old zones, update them.  Chardok was empty until it was updated, and now it has more activity.  Other zones can get similar treatment and see similar results.  How long the increased population stays will be based on how well the changes are implemented.<br>
<br>
