<br>
However, there is a very limited gaming populace, probably around 1500-2000 people on any given server max at peak times.  That was pretty awful back before the expansions, it left nowhere to hunt and bad lag.  But the world is about three TIMES as big as it used to be, and those people are now scattered around all over the place.  You just cannot have every zone full of people all the time - there isn't the population to fill them all up!  It's OK for some dungeons to be empty, like Nurga for instance, if they are otherwise well done.  The reason to change a dungeon is because it sucks or needs work, not because it's empty.  Some places will always have light traffic, there's just not enough people to go everywhere at once. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/utargonis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 631<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/11/02 10:24 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Can game balance happen without a change to the old worl</span><hr size=1> I never once said that the mobs should be made MORE powerful.  I repeat, they should not be made more powerful, just that they don't have the 32k HP cap.  The way to do this is simple, tune the damage output of the mobs to compensate for them having more hit points.  The encounter will be longer, but with lower damage output from the mob(s), it's the same difficulty, just a longer encounter.<br>
<br>
Most of us old timers remember how they boosted the damage output of mobs when Kunark was released, and this increased with Velious.  If the number of hit points that a mob does goes up, the way you keep it the same overall difficulty is to lower the damage output of the mobs.  This is also a way to reduce mudflation, to use this sort of thing when you tune encounters.  You can boost AC to make something more difficult to kill, boost HP, raise or LOWER the damage output to compensate, etc.<br>
<br>
So, one more time if you missed it, raising hit points past the 32k HP limit doesn't mean that the encounter MUST be more difficult as a result if you tune the encounter properly.<br>
